				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">While not trying to get into the middle of this arguement, I believe the point in question wasn't the success rate of a full quad, it was the fact that pets inherantly hit for max much more often than a PC does.  Nobody can actually say exactly what a fully buffed pets attack rating is, but comparing my warder to myself, with self buffs only and around 1700 attack, I hit for max around 12% of the time.  My warder hits for max around 40-50% of the time with each successful hit, depnding of course on the mob in question and positioning.
<br />

<br />
At least I am assuming that is what he was trying to say.  The debate over how often the Beastial Frenzy AA allows a Bst to complete a double attack, just as a bard with maxed ability, has nothing to do with skill.  It's more of a random % roll generated by the RNG, and not based on skill caps.  Parsing may show that over a long period of time may show that a lower DA skill cap of 70 is close the ability's overall success rate, however in short battles is is very inconsistant and spiky.  I can go a full fight without it firing, then the next fight make out a few triples and a full quad.  Bst and mage pets alike have innate skill caps based similarly on PC skill caps that determine mainhand and offhand attack DA attempts, and do so much more frequently because of this as it is calculated with each attempt.
<br />

<br />
I like the concept of being able to toggle the mage pet in between defensive and offensive abilities, because that covers both of the sides desires when it comes to balancing the mage class.  Many mages rejoiced over the pet getting buffed defensively with the recent changes, while others still were upset that the pets offensive abilities were not tweeked.  This would cover both sides and allow mage to have more control over what type of exping/raiding they do more often.  However, I don't think it would be all that useful to give the fire and water pet this ability, as it water would do considerably less damage than intended in the tanking posistion and would not have the greater innate mitigation of RS or the stun of WoX.  Also in concerns with the fire pet, 61+ I can't see any of his abilities being worthwhile for tanking as his melee, even if tweaked, is horrid, and his innate DS would mean little to PoP/GoD mobs and damage output.
<br />

<br />
I can't speak for MS4 as I don't have this pet yet, bleh.  I'm not sure why the comparision of melee with PoTime+ weapons to pets has any bearing on this, as we all know the devs would not make a pet that = the DPS of a top DPS melee and not take into consideration the DPS the pet master also contributes.  I can visualize a pet possibly quadding for 150, but I can't see anything past that untill OoW possibly.  Who knows what that will bring.  As of right now the spell lists look pretty generic, and we have no idea yet what possibly abilities/AA's it will bring with it.  I wonder how they are going to adjust the laps in skill cap changes for the melee classes in regards to 60-65 having no changes, but will most likely have a higher cap in OoW (hint, this will also affect pets as we already have pets with focus above level 60)
<br />

<br />
Elder Longfanz Feral Lord</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
